The laptop body is aluminium built but it is not that tough, while lifting the laptop you can hear those cracky sound which will disappoint you a lot. Otherwise overall design is good but not best.  Display:  No negative comments on display no laptop offers you such display in this price range. You will absolutely love it's display. It could have been much better if there was Anti glare display, but to be honest it doesn't make that much of difference. The thing which i liked the most about this laptop is its display  Value For Money:  I got this laptop in Rs42000 only and i am fully satisfied with this, getting such laptop with so many flagship specs at this price is undoubtedly the best option. After having used the laptop for 2 weeks I can comfortably say that where Realme lacks in brand value it makes up in design and quality. Performance: i3 model has enough power for daily use. UI is smooth and responsive and web browsing and binging netflix is a delight. Screen: 2k resolution with accurate colors is an eye candy. However the brightness levels isn't adequate and the glossy screen is unusable outdoors. Best for indoor use. Battery: Average. 5-6 hours with balanced setting. Although the fast charger makes life a little easier. Can make through a full day on a full charge. Build quality: Excellent. Aluminum chassis with minimum flex. Feels good to hold. However the hinge is plastic and doesn't feel durable. Keyboard speakers etc. Average to seasoned users coming from a higher teir laptop. To all other users it is quite usable.

The following is a detailed usage review. First of all, I Thank Flipkart for the fast delivery, that too a day before the promised delivery date. This is by far the best laptop you could get for the price range. As a person who have been a windows user all my life, MacOS is a totally different experience for me. The aluminium build, the performance, the display and the compactness of this machine has surprised me.  PROS: 1. The M1 Chip - This chip is the sole reason that narrowed me down to the Air in the price range (i.e. below INR 1Lakh). The chip is a beast and it can tackle almost 90-95% tasks you throw at it, that too without heating issues. It is ARM-based, and contains both the CPU and GPU in a single unit. The RAM is also integrated within it, with both the CPU and GPU having ready access to it, thereby reducing the time needed to access data across circuits like in other laptops. The performance is on par with many high-end laptops. Hats Off to Apple for designing this revolutionary chip. 2. No heating issues* - The M1 chip is so power-efficient, that almost every task is done without any heating issues. The Air could go hours without any heating. *This is for daily tasks which include web browsing, reading PDFs, making presentations, photo and light video editing. 3. Battery backup - With a 49Wh battery powering the M1, the battery backup is phenomenal. With the above mentioned tasks in point no. 2, it would easily last 3-4 days once fully charged. I‚Äôve tested the charging time from 0-100% to be 2Hrs 45Mins with a 30W adapter. The charging time can be reduced with a faster adapter. 4. Fan-less design - No fan means no background noise while doing heavy tasks. The M1 chip without a fan is more than enough for 90% of users. 5. Light weight - The sleek aluminium build makes it light weight and easy to carry. Being a 13-inch device, it fits easily in small backpacks. A premium sleeve would help protect it from accidental falls or bumps. 6. Trackpad - One of the best features that I love about this device! The feedback is amazing with plenty of swipe gestures that make multitasking hassle-free. The trackpad is big with plenty of space to move around. 7. Keyboard - The keyboard is great with good key travel and clicky keys. 8. Display - It has a 2560*1600 Retina display with excellent colour reproduction. I own an Zenbook 15 and while colour grading photos on both the devices I‚Äôve found the colour reproduction of the Air to be far superior. 9. Speakers - The speakers are great with good volume levels. If you‚Äôre a person who listens to music on the laptop speakers, do consider the Pro as it comes with HDR Speakers.  CONS 1. Not for heavy video editing/gaming - The M1 Air is best for editing videos upto 1080p with little or no heating. It also runs light games, but is not meant for heavy gaming. If you‚Äôre a video editor who edits heavy 4K files, the Air would eventually get it done, but its better to go for the Pro as it has an extra core and a fan. Same is the case for heavy gamers, it would be better to upgrade the RAM and opt for the extra core. 2. No LED Indicator - A charging indicator should‚Äôve been included either on the Air or on the adapter. Its handy to have an indicator to know that your device is fully charged. The only way to find out at present is to switch-on the device and check. 3. USB ports - The thin and light build does come with some drawbacks in the form of lack of ports. It is included with 2 Thunderbolt ports (one for charging) and a 3.5mm audio jack. The thunderbolt ports are both on the same side, placed close to each other. Some users may find it difficult if they plan to connect 2 usb-c devices together. It would‚Äôve been convenient if they were on opposite sides. People who wish to connect SD cards, flash drives or external hard disks one should consider getting a 7 in 1 usb-hub. 4. WebCam - For a device that stands out in the price range, the camera you get on it is not something that impresses you. Its provided with only a 720p camera. Apple says it uses software optimisation to make it look good and it does to some extent, but I believe they could do better. 5. Display glossiness - The display is a bit glossy and would catch reflections if used outdoors. It has 400nits of brightness, which helps with the viewing angles to an extent. You can always get a matte finish screen protector, but it could interfere with the colour reproduction of the display.  I hope this review helps to decide whether the Air M1 is the best one for you. I‚Äôve got the 256GB variant with 8GB RAM and I believe its more than enough for 90% of users. Getting an external ssd to store your files and documents could help free up the system storage for your applications to run smooth. If you‚Äôre not a heavy gamer or a video editor, the MacBook Air M1 is the best value for money laptop that‚Äôs available on the market at present. Just go for it!

Amazing with respect to the price.  The Noise cancellation modes are good, In the transparent mode you feel like you are wearing nothing. You get to hear all the environmental sounds as if you are wearing nothing in the ear. The Normal mode is a bit like the Passive noise cancellation with help of the tight earbuds only. Still you get to hear some mild sounds from outside. In the Active Noise Cancellation (ANC) mode you are in space..! No outside sound at all. Totally blank.  During call, other person complained about my voice being good but not crystal clear like in the wired earphones.  Very lightweight & good build quality.  Very good sound quality (with sony LDAC)  Very good battery backup (Depending on various parameters, such as usage of ANC, Sony LDAC will reduce the battery life)

I was able to experience every feature and element of quality that makes the Apple Airpods Pro so special and magical! Good sound quality, comfort, great controls, transparency mode, call quality, great noise cancellation, super fast charging, almost 5 hours of battery backup on a single charge, spatial audio, seamless multi device switching. No other earbuds offers these features at the level of quality and standard Apple enables us to experience.  However, here comes the catch. I'm not sure if I'm wildly unlucky or if there are quirks happening with others too, but the transparency mode on my right earbuds stopped working after two months.  Even this is fine, I thought maybe I got a defective piece and that I can replace it under warranty. However, when I gave it to the Apple Authorized service center, they took my earbuds for a week to diagnose. A week later they call me to collect saying there is no issue with the earbud, AS THEIR DIAGNOSTIC SOFTWARE DID NOT DETECT AN ISSUE WITH THE EARBUD, when it is so evident that the transparency mode does not work on my right earbud anymore. They said that THEY CANNOT REPLACE THE EARBUD UNDER WARRANTY even though the issue is evident BECAUSE THEIR "DIAGNOSIS" did not detect the issue.  I have escalated the issue directly to Apple. Hoping to get a resolution soon.

The best television brands are always Sony, Samsung, LG because of their panel, picture and sound quality. Other brands like Mi, Vu are all secondary brands and the quality difference compared to the best brands are very much visible without looking at the specification itself. This is where I was amazed getting the Infinix television. The specification comparison with brands like Samsung was sort of close to identical. After using it I will definitely say Infinix brand has every right to be among the list of best brands and not in the secondary brand list. We can check the screen quality by touching the screen and by doing so we will see pressure points. The best brands won't show lighter shade pressure points or no pressure points at all. But the secondary brands will have darkish pressure points. Infinix television has got only lighter shade pressure point. Anyone without technical knowledge could check the screen quality in this manner. I will write some pros and cons below:  Pros 1. Great picture and sound quality. 2. Great connectivity. 3. Looks premium. 4. Easy set up. 5. Easy remote functionality. 6. Installation was very good and prompt.  Cons Haven't seen any cons for this television as of now but I do want to check how the service centre experience will be like. That doesn't change the quality of the product though.  Got this model for Rs 10,000+ which is a great buy because it's definitely worth Rs 20,000+. If you can't afford a Samsung or Sony, Infinix can become the next choice without compromising on quality.

It's my secondary TV and i purchased for my home office where I can occasionally watch some OTT series or live cricket. I exchange this with my 32 inch 10 yo LCD as i was struggling to watch OTT content on the same. So my initial first impresions: 40 inch size is perfect for 12x12 room and it's very light in weight and also thin bezels. Pros: 1. Good picture quality, brightness is superb with 350 Nits ( but not to be compared with LG or Sony) l. Better than some rivals at similar price range. 2. Bluetooth connectivity with my Bose soundlink is flawless with absolutely no lag/delay. However I noticed that audio gets disconnected for a sec intermittently during the video. If this is a Software issue, company should fix with update. 3.Light remote however there was no need of number pad. 4. Bezel less design and it's looks great in the wall. 5. Sound is not great but not bad too, it's average. Dolby seems to be a gimmick. 6. Lastly, it's high value for money  Cons: 1. Biggest, why there is no 5Ghz wifi support? 2. Wall mount is missing, they should at least provide screws for wall mount and just not for table top only. 3. 1GB RAM with just 8 gb storage is letdown as there are many OTT apps nowadays. sluggish interface, takes around 2 minutes post restart for apps to become fully functional. 4. 2 gen old Android version which is Android TV 9. Infinix can ramp up their sales by providing atleast Android TV 10. Some of other brands are already providing Android TV 11.   Overall ,i like picture quality which is FHD and it's a great value for money if anyone is under 20k. Go for it, easily comparable with brands that offers same specs but at more price. Only apprehension, company should focus more on customer retention as to provide updates and more models to customers.

Let's get the unimpressive out of the way. I'm not satisfied with the Android OS experience on this TV. The OS works fine and smooth for the most part, but on occasion the interface would lag, and button presses take several seconds to be registered. This occasional choppy UI experience doesn't feel pleasant at all. This may have to do more with issues in the Android OS than anything with the TV hardware. But, anyone looking for a TV specifically for smart features may look at other options in this price segment.  Now, on to the display. I am overall pleased with the display quality. The display is a VA panel which produces good enough contrast. The downside of a VA panel is relatively poor viewing angles, which is not ideal for family viewing. For the colour reproduction, initially the colours looked off (too saturated) in the deep Reds. I went in the Settings and reduced the saturation for Red and then in the "10 point color" setting, reduced the saturation for Reds with 70% gain and above. And, this did improve the image, and now the colours look fairly balanced. Also, the Sharpness setting should be kept at zero, anything above adds artificial sharpening to the image.  And the remote which connects via Bluetooth, works fine, has a textured back and feels nice in the hand.  All in all, for a dumb TV, this is a really good option. And, for smart features, I can't say how it compares with other similarly priced TVs.

The display is good, and I use to as my daily office monitor for work from home. The platform which I work on, the websites looks perfect and I do not have to squint my eyes like I used to do in my 14" laptop provided by my office. Sure there is pixel bleeding from the edges, and pixels can be separated if you look very closely, but who will go that close to a monitor. One thing to note, this isn't suited for gaming, which demands high refresh rate and low response time, but for content consumption, it is perfect. This may not be suited for gaming, but I still play GTA V in it, and I've got kinda used to it, so it doesn't bother me anymore. If you wanna purchase to sit a bit apart from the monitor, which I'm sure you should do for a 27" monitor, and use it for office purpose, or content consumption, this is really good.  One another to note, I could not claim my warranty, since the website given in the warranty card is not accessible.  But all in all, this is a good monitor.

22MP68VQ and 22MK600M both have same specification except 3 spec  1. 22MP68VQ IS 2016 MODEL BUT 22MK600M IS 2018 MODEL and the Manufacturing date may vary in both the models 2. 22MP68VQ has VGA, DVI, HDMI and audio out ports - 22MK600M has VGA, 2 HDMI and audio out ports  3. MOST IMPORTANT IS DISPLAY (Panel Bit depth) 22MP68VQ is 8 bits panel and 22MK600M is 8 bits (6 bits + FRC) which is low quality and low cost display than 8 Bits panel. 6 Bits + FRC panel is a 6 bits panel and it try to show image like 8 bits panel using FRC  If you need a crisp and clear display blindly go for 22MP68VQ

The keyboard layout is different from a laptop and hence you have to adjust yourself to the new layout. 3. You have to use a mouse as a substitute for touch pad and hence you almost become a desktop user with the new set up. 4. If we want to use it for a laptop and if you are buying it for saving you from neck pain, back pain, the concept is good, but it is better to buy a keyboard with exact similar layout. 5. Ideal keyboard would be the one with a touch pad. But I couldn‚Äôt find a good model with a good review and there were one or two models costing 10K plus which i didn‚Äôt venture into. 6. It's a good, compact and premium looking HDD. I was not able to connect this HDD with my mobile (one plus 5) then later on doing some RND work, I found out below two observations: 1. I bought a new USB to type C connector (type C connecter given in box was working for me on laptop but not for mobile-power was not reaching to HDD) 2. I disabled the password encryption feature of HDD  After doing above two things I was then able to connect this HDD to my mobile phone.  Space available was 1.82 TB. Speed is also good. I bought it for 4500Rs in big billion sale with help of bank offer and discounts etc.  Also don't forget to buy a cover for your HDD, coz it'll keep your HDD safe.
